Pirithous attempted to carry off Proserpine. It has been well suggested that the mythological instances selected by Horace in these stanzas are selected with a definite purpose : they are all instances of those whom lust has ruined -temptator Orion, incontinens Tityos, amator Pirithous, Considering to whom the Ode is addressed and whose victories are suggested, there can be little doubt who the fallen foe hinted at is,--the Roman Antony who had

perished in the meshes of Cleopatra. For similar eloquent omissions of his name cf. 1. 37 Int., 3. 8. 18 n.
